<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Co-founder Experience | Raunak Jalan</title>
  <link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href="/favicon.svg" />
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
  <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Space+Grotesk:wght@400;500;700&family=Playfair+Display:ital@1&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
</head>
<body>

<div id="proj-startup" style="display: block;">
  <nav class="proj-nav animate-pill">
    <a href="/#works" class="back-btn" style="text-decoration:none;"><span class="back-arr">←</span> All projects</a>
  </nav>

  <div class="startup-hero">
    <h1 class="startup-headline">
      <span class="animate-blog-1" style="display:block;">Not all ideas</span>
      <span class="dim-line animate-blog-2" style="display:block;">go through.</span>
    </h1>
    <p class="startup-sub">Some ideas are right but the timing is off. Some teams are solid but the alignment isn't. Ours was probably both. This is the honest version of what happened — and what I'd do differently.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Tags -->
  <div style="padding: 2rem 3rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
    <span class="ptag">Hardware</span>
    <span class="ptag">EV / Micromobility</span>
    <span class="ptag">D2C</span>
    <span class="ptag">IIT Kanpur</span>
    <span class="ptag">Hyundai HOPE Scholar</span>
    <span class="ptag">2024</span>
    <span class="ptag">Stealth → Wound Down</span>
  </div>

  <!-- Metrics strip -->
  <div class="metrics-strip">
    <div class="metric-item">
      <span class="metric-val">₹1.25L</span>
      <span class="metric-label">Non-dilutive funding</span>
    </div>
    <div class="metric-divider"></div>
    <div class="metric-item">
      <span class="metric-val">100 km</span>
      <span class="metric-label">Validated range</span>
    </div>
    <div class="metric-divider"></div>
    <div class="metric-item">
      <span class="metric-val">25 km/h</span>
      <span class="metric-label">Speed cap — license free</span>
    </div>
    <div class="metric-divider"></div>
    <div class="metric-item">
      <span class="metric-val">₹25–30k</span>
      <span class="metric-label">Target price point</span>
    </div>
    <div class="metric-divider"></div>
    <div class="metric-item">
      <span class="metric-val">~6 mo</span>
      <span class="metric-label">Grant to working MVP</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="proj-body" style="max-width:680px;margin:0 auto;">

    <div class="proj-section">
      <div class="proj-section-label">The Idea</div>
      <p class="proj-p">India has a quiet mobility gap. You can buy a cycle for ₹5,000–10,000 or a scooter for ₹60,000+. The space in between — affordable, electric, license-free personal transport — is almost entirely empty. That's where we wanted to build.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">The product was a Low Speed Electric Vehicle (LSEV) bike capped at 25 km/h — which means no driving license required under Indian motor vehicle law. Our target wasn't the EV enthusiast who wants a fancy Ather. It was the college student who can't afford a scooter, the delivery agent trying to cut fuel costs, the elderly person who can no longer get a license, and the micro-entrepreneur in a tier-3 town who needs something durable and cheap to run.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">The economics worked on paper and — crucially — on the road too. We designed for a sub-₹30,000 price point without subsidy (government EV subsidies could bring it lower), with a 100 km range and the lowest operating cost per km in the segment. D2C first, with B2B plays around institutional and government tie-ups as a second layer.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="proj-section">
      <div class="proj-section-label">What We Built</div>
      <p class="proj-p">Not a deck. An actual bike.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">Starting from scratch, we designed the chassis, sourced the motor, battery, and controller through a Kanpur-based company in our professor's network that specialised in e-rickshaw components, and assembled a fully working prototype on IIT Kanpur campus. Our budget was ₹1.25 lakhs — a non-dilutive Hyundai HOPE Scholarship grant — and we stretched it as far as it could go.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">We ran multiple range tests (100 km validated), clocked speed runs, and handed the bike to two real users — one male, one female — for daily commute testing on campus. We collected structured UX feedback and mapped the next design iteration around it. The roadmap from there was clear: build 4–5 improved units, run a formal on-campus pilot with IITK admin approval, then pursue government certification and legal clearance.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">We got further than most teams do before raising a rupee.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="proj-section">
      <div class="proj-section-label">What Went Wrong</div>
      <p class="proj-p">I've thought about this honestly. A few things converged.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">The founding was accidental, not conviction-driven. We built it because a grant appeared — not because either of us was losing sleep over this problem. That difference matters more than it seems. Passion is the fuel for the unsexy weeks where nothing moves. We had genuine interest in the idea; we needed obsession in the problem.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">The team didn't hold. We started with 5–6 people. By the end it was effectively two of us and a professor. Our faculty mentor was excellent on the EV and battery side, but business execution was never going to come from him — and we leaned on him for things he couldn't deliver. And between me and my co-founder, we weren't misaligned on the idea, we were running at different intensities. When a VC came to campus to review startups, I was genuinely excited. He wasn't. That gap is hard to close mid-flight.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">Staying in stealth was also a mistake. We told ourselves we'd go public once we had something real. What it actually did was remove all external accountability. No one was waiting for us, no one was watching, so slowing down had no cost. The next step after the pilot was clear. We just never took it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="proj-section">
      <div class="proj-section-label">What I Took From It</div>
      <p class="proj-p">Passion isn't optional — it's the infrastructure everything else runs on. The slow days, the blocked approvals, the mentor who doesn't follow through — you only push through those if the problem actually matters to you. Interest gets you started. Obsession keeps you going.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">I also learned what it means to build under real constraints. ₹1.25L for a hardware prototype is almost nothing. We sourced smartly, leveraged the right networks, and shipped something physical that actually worked. That scrappiness — knowing which corners to cut and which ones you can't — is something I'd carry into any operator or growth role.</p>
      <p class="proj-p">And I got a direct education in co-founder dynamics that no blog post could teach. Misalignment isn't always visible disagreement. Sometimes it's one person who's fully in, and one who's mostly in. That gap — quiet, subtle, growing — is often what kills a team before the market ever gets the chance.</p>
      <p class="proj-p" style="color: rgba(240,239,235,0.45); font-style: italic;">If I were starting over: I'd have put up a waitlist on day one, charged ₹99 for early access, and let external pressure do what internal motivation couldn't.</p>
    </div>

  </div>

  <footer>
    <span>Raunak Jalan — 2026</span>
    <a href="/#works" class="btn-ghost" style="font-size:12px; text-decoration:none;">← Back to all projects</a>
  </footer>
</div>

<script is:inline>
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      document.documentElement.classList.add('reveal-ready');
    }, 50);
  });
</script>

</body>
</html>

